    Wristwatches - the ultimate style statement


    Buying the perfect wristwatch is not just a regular event in a person’s life. It is actually nothing short of a veritable rite of passage, that an individual has to go through. You know why it is so important to find the perfect watch? It is because watches not only help you keep a track of time but also make a strong style statement. With so many options available on online shopping sites from various brands like Rado , Citizen, Tag Heuer , Longines, Breitling, Franck Muller, Cartier, Omega, Guess, Police, Diesel, Fossil, Giordano, Skmei, Tommy Hilfiger, Casio, Titan, Fastrack and Timex, even the most suave of person’s can get tripped up while looking for the perfect watches. Don’t get overwhelmed and let us take you through a few steps that will help you buy the perfect timepiece for your wrist.


    Decide on the type of wristwatch you want to buy.


    Wristwatches, like a sexy dress or a pair of impeccable shoes, add to your overall look. Before even looking online, you need to decide what kind of a watch you want to go for and whether it will suit your personality. Timepieces are complex things, and what makes them different from one another is their method of timekeeping. Let us look at the different types of watches based on their timekeeping methods and faces.

    Digital watches - These kinds of watches feature a digital face that read out time in exact numbers. Most of these watches are loaded with other features such altimeters and depth sensors, and are great for outdoor activities like sports. 

    Analogue quartz watches - When a watch has a dial with numbers, Roman numerals, dots or stones to mark time, it is known as an analogue watch. They are the oldest kinds of watches and are popular with both the old and young generation. These watches, with their classic appeal, go well with any kind of outfit.

    Analogue-digital watches - These timepieces are a combination of both digital and analogue watches, as they feature an analogue dial that also displays time in the digital format.

    Automatic mechanical watches - These types of watches use the movements of your wrist to keep the mechanism inside running. They usually feature a rotor swing encased in a transparent or partially transparent display. 

    Manual mechanical watches - These classic watches contain a power reserve and need to be wound daily to tighten the spring and function properly. 

    Smart watches - The latest trend in wrist watches is smartwatches. Loaded with so many features such as calculator, fitness sensors, phonebook and heart-rate monitor, these watches can be easily synced with your smartphones. You can also use these kinds of watches to pick up calls and read instant messages. 


    What to look for next when buying a wristwatch?


    Now that you know about the types of watches available online, let us look at the range of materials for wristwatches and their straps that you can choose from.

    Stainless steel - As it is a durable and strong material that can withstand shock and impact gracefully, stainless steel is often used in making watches. Timepieces made of this metal are also rust-proof.

    Aluminum - Watches made of this metal are usually resistant to corrosion and tarnish, which makes them perfect for daily wear. They are also durable and often lightweight.

    Titanium - Watches made from this strong metal are often sturdy, lightweight and resistant to corrosion. You can usually see the use of this metal in the making of sports watches that often are exposed to the elements of nature.

    Plastic or rubber - Mostly popular with the young generation, wristwatches with rubber or plastic straps and dial casing come in bright and peppy colors. These are also slightly less expensive than their metal or leather counterparts.

    Leather or faux-leather - Timepieces with leather straps have a classic appeal and go mostly with formal outfits. You also get watches with faux-leather straps that are less expensive than the leather strap ones.

    Precious metals - Some of the high-end wristwatches like Rolex, Movado, Rado and Tag Heuer have watches made of precious metals like gold and platinum. Ultimate in luxury, some of these feature dials that use real diamonds to mark time.
